OpenGL Milky Way
===========================================================================

![Milky Way](screenshot.png)

This is an example project to show how to render a Galaxy in OpenGL. To
simulate interstellar dust realistically with unsorted point sprites, it uses a
GPU based ray tracing algorithm. This Milky Way model is used in the
[Exoplanet App](http://exoplanetapp.com), which is available for free on the
AppStore and contains several other datasets.

I gave a talk about this project at the New York iOS Meetup in January 2013.
The [slides](https://github.com/hannorein/OpenGLMilkyWay/raw/master/2012%20NY%20iOS%20Meetup.pdf)
of the talk are included in this repository. For comments, questions, or
suggestions: exoplanet@hanno-rein.de.

## Architecture

The renderer is a **shared C++ core** (`core/`) that targets pure OpenGL ES 2.0,
driven by thin platform shells:

```
core/                        # shared C++ (GLES2, no Obj-C, no JNI)
├── src/
│   ├── MilkyWayRenderer.{cpp,h}   # 3-pass frame: bg quad → 256² dust FBO → points
│   ├── ShaderProgram.{cpp,h}      # compile/link/query, uniform cache
│   ├── ArcballCamera.{cpp,h}      # quaternion arcball + pinch + roll, velocity decay
│   └── AssetProvider.h            # interface: name -> bytes (platform implements)
├── third_party/
│   ├── stb_image.h                # PNG decode (replaces UIImage/Texture2D)
│   └── linmath.h                  # mat4/quat math (replaces GLKit math)
└── assets/                        # canonical shared assets
    └── *.vsh *.fsh  milkyway0.binary  milkywaybg/dust.png  newblob.png  sun_marker.png

OpenGLMilkyWay/             # iOS app shell (MetalANGLE / MGLKit)
android/                    # Android app shell (Gradle + NDK/CMake)
third_party/metalangle/     # MetalANGLE framework (fetched, gitignored)
```

### Astronomical accuracy

The renderer carries the galaxy's current best-understood structure (all knobs
live in `core/src/MilkyWayConventions.h`, cited):

- **Two major stellar arms** (Scutum–Centaurus, Perseus) anchored at the central
  bar — the post-2008 Spitzer-era model, depicted in `milkywaybg.png`.
- **Gaia galactic warp** — the outer stellar disk (R > 9 kpc) is bent into the
  classic S-shape measured by Gaia DR2 Cepheid mapping (Chen et al. 2019;
  Skowron et al. 2019). Applied as a load-time transform on the 65k-star
  catalog (zero per-frame cost); face-on it's invisible, edge-on it shows the
  integral-sign profile that flat artwork cannot.
- **Sun marker** (toggle on/off via the ⊕ button) at ~8.2 kpc from the
  galactic center on the Local (Orion) Spur (Gravity Collaboration 2019).

> **Artist's impression informed by Spitzer & Gaia survey data — not a
> photograph.** Base artwork: NASA/JPL-Caltech/R. Hurt (SSC); star catalog and
> warp model by the port authors from the cited survey data.
```

### iOS

The original 2012 app used Apple's *deprecated* OpenGL ES + GLKit. It now runs
on **[MetalANGLE](https://github.com/kakashidinho/metalangle)** — GL-over-Metal —
which removes the `OpenGLES.framework`/`GLKit.framework` dependencies entirely:

- `GLKViewController` → `MGLKViewController`, `GLKView` → `MGLKView`,
  `EAGLContext` → `MGLContext(kMGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2)`.
- `UniverseViewController` is thin glue: owns the core objects, forwards
  gestures/resize/draw, keeps the on-screen buttons + Share controller.
- `AppleAssetProvider` bridges `mw::AssetProvider` to `NSBundle`.

To fetch the (gitignored) MetalANGLE framework:
```sh
tools/fetch_metalangle.sh   # installs sim + device slices under third_party/metalangle/
```
Then open `OpenGLMilkyWay.xcodeproj` and run on an iPhone or the simulator.
At launch the app logs `GL_RENDERER = ANGLE (Metal Renderer: …)`, confirming
the GL calls are serviced by Metal via ANGLE.

### Android

A standard Gradle + NDK/CMake project (`android/`). `MainActivity` hosts a
`GLSurfaceView` (GLES2, RGBA8888); the JNI bridge (`milkyway_jni.cpp`) compiles
the shared `core/` into one `libmilkyway.so` and exposes
`nativeInit/Resize/DrawFrame/Pan/Pinch/Roll/Update`. Gestures are mapped to the
same arcball/pinch/roll model as iOS. Shared assets are referenced from
`core/assets` (no duplication).

ANGLE is opted into via the manifest (`uses-native-library`,
`required="false"`, API 31+); on the Android 14+ emulator the renderer reports
`ANGLE (… SwiftShader …)`.

```sh
cd android
./gradlew :app:assembleDebug
adb install -r app/build/outputs/apk/debug/app-debug.apk
adb shell am start -n de.hanno_rein.milkyway/.MainActivity
```

